RISK CALCULATION SHEET
For this assignment I identified risks across six categories: financial, operational, competitive, reputational, technical, and legal and regulatory and to score each risk on a 1-to-5 scale for both likelihood and impact.
Up to nine risks were identified within each category, drawing on Canada Life's corporate disclosures, current market intelligence, and regulatory developments. 

FINANCIAL
Santé Circle may have been overvalued at purchase
Hidden financial obligations may increase costs unexpectedly
Cross-selling Canada Life products to Santé Circle clients may be harder than expected
Absorbing Santé Circle's risk portfolio will likely raise reinsurance costs
Foreign currency contracts may cause unexpected exchange losses
Maintaining two IT roadmaps is straining the capital budget
Unifying both platforms may cost significantly more than budgeted
If synergies don't materialise, a goodwill write-down may be required
Digital transformation costs could exceed the board-approved budget

OPERATIONAL
Unclear roles are slowing day-to-day work
Key wellness staff may leave rather than adapt to a corporate environment
Aligning benefits administration will take more time and money than projected
Poor team alignment could lead to inconsistent client service
Running two systems simultaneously increases costs and creates uneven experiences
Poor project communication could cause delays and duplicated work
Cultural differences may cause friction between the two workforces
Without proper training, staff and clients may be slow to adopt new tools
Without shared KPIs, measuring integration progress will be difficult

COMPETITIVE
Long-term clients may switch to competitors post-merger
Merged entity may struggle to differentiate from cheaper digital competitors
Competitors may actively target Santé Circle clients during the transition
A slow integration may cause the entity to miss the growing mental health market
Large corporate clients may delay renewals amid merger uncertainty
Competitors may lower prices or run targeted campaigns in response to Canada Life's growth
Competitors may secure key employer partnerships before integration is complete
Santé Circle's boutique model may not scale easily to a national client base
A slow integration could cause Canada Life to miss Indigenous community health opportunities

REPUTATIONAL
Service disruptions could erode policyholder confidence
Past service complaints from Santé Circle could surface and damage reputation
Brokers loyal to Santé Circle may stop recommending the merged entity
Announcing layoffs during integration may attract negative media coverage
Clients accustomed to Santé Circle's personal approach may feel overlooked
Clients in regions with local Santé Circle ties may feel community connection is lost
Publicly challenged AI-influenced benefit decisions could raise practice concerns
Clients who valued Santé Circle's smaller size may publicly express dissatisfaction
Mishandling client health data during the transition could trigger regulatory action

TECHNICAL
Telehealth platform may not connect with Canada Life's systems
Health data models may not be reliable for Canada Life's underwriting
A poor cross-platform experience could frustrate clients and increase complaints
Third-party health apps may introduce cybersecurity vulnerabilities
System downtime during peak renewal periods could create large backlogs
Some AI triage tools may not meet Health Canada standards
Without a shared data governance framework, performance reporting will be inconsistent
Cloud hosting of combined client data may raise provincial data residency concerns
Santé Circle's predictive models may degrade as their training data ages

LEGAL/ COMPLIANCE
Deal could be delayed if OSFI approvals were not fully secured
Transferring client records without consent could breach Quebec's Law 25
Canada Life's larger market share may attract Competition Bureau scrutiny
Disputes over jointly developed IP could delay new services
Wellness programmes without consent processes may expose Canada Life to claims
Sharing client health data across provinces without consent could violate privacy law
Differences in HR policies could lead to employment law violations
Non-solicitation clauses may limit Canada Life's ability to market to Santé Circle clients
Poorly reviewed indemnity clauses may leave Canada Life liable for Santé Circle's past claims

